21. bxc3 - white's queenside pawns are a mess!  Not only that, black has a rook that controls the whole d file.  White cannot contest the d file because the d2 square is controlled by the black dsb.  The dsb must move, however, because it is en prise to the white rook on a2.  So black plays Bd3 which is a strong move because if the lsbs are exchanged then the d8 rook can come to d3 where it will be a cat among pigeons as I explain in a later note.
